ER.GDP.FWTL.M3.KD-fj.def: Water productivity is calculated as GDP in constant prices divided by annual total water withdrawal.
ER.GDP.FWTL.M3.KD-fj.name: Water productivity, total
ER.GDP.FWTL.M3.KD-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
ER.GDP.FWTL.M3.KD-fj.units: constant 2010 US$ GDP per cubic meter of total freshwater withdrawal

ER.H2O.FWAG.ZS-fj.def: Annual freshwater withdrawals refer to total water withdrawals, not counting evaporation losses from storage basins. Withdrawals also include water from desalination plants in countries where they are a significant source. Withdrawals can exceed 100 percent of total renewable resources where extraction from nonrenewable aquifers or desalination plants is considerable or where there is significant water reuse. Withdrawals for agriculture are total withdrawals for irrigation and livestock production. Data are for the most recent year available for 1987-2002.
ER.H2O.FWAG.ZS-fj.name: Annual freshwater withdrawals
ER.H2O.FWAG.ZS-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.

ER.H2O.FWDM.ZS-fj.def: Annual freshwater withdrawals refer to total water withdrawals, not counting evaporation losses from storage basins. Withdrawals also include water from desalination plants in countries where they are a significant source. Withdrawals can exceed 100 percent of total renewable resources where extraction from nonrenewable aquifers or desalination plants is considerable or where there is significant water reuse. Withdrawals for domestic uses include drinking water, municipal use or supply, and use for public services, commercial establishments, and homes. Data are for the most recent year available for 1987-2002.
ER.H2O.FWDM.ZS-fj.name: Annual freshwater withdrawals
ER.H2O.FWDM.ZS-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.

ER.H2O.FWIN.ZS-fj.def: Annual freshwater withdrawals refer to total water withdrawals, not counting evaporation losses from storage basins. Withdrawals also include water from desalination plants in countries where they are a significant source. Withdrawals can exceed 100 percent of total renewable resources where extraction from nonrenewable aquifers or desalination plants is considerable or where there is significant water reuse. Withdrawals for industry are total withdrawals for direct industrial use (including withdrawals for cooling thermoelectric plants). Data are for the most recent year available for 1987-2002.
ER.H2O.FWIN.ZS-fj.name: Annual freshwater withdrawals
ER.H2O.FWIN.ZS-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.

ER.H2O.FWST.ZS-fj.def: The level of water stress: freshwater withdrawal as a proportion of available freshwater resources is the ratio between total freshwater withdrawn by all major sectors and total renewable freshwater resources, after taking into account environmental water requirements. Main sectors, as defined by ISIC standards, include agriculture; forestry and fishing; manufacturing; electricity industry; and services. This indicator is also known as water withdrawal intensity.
ER.H2O.FWST.ZS-fj.name: Level of water stress: freshwater withdrawal as a proportion of available freshwater resources
ER.H2O.FWST.ZS-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.

ER.H2O.FWTL.K3-fj.def: Annual freshwater withdrawals refer to total water withdrawals, not counting evaporation losses from storage basins. Withdrawals also include water from desalination plants in countries where they are a significant source. Withdrawals can exceed 100 percent of total renewable resources where extraction from nonrenewable aquifers or desalination plants is considerable or where there is significant water reuse. Withdrawals for agriculture and industry are total withdrawals for irrigation and livestock production and for direct industrial use (including withdrawals for cooling thermoelectric plants). Withdrawals for domestic uses include drinking water, municipal use or supply, and use for public services, commercial establishments, and homes. Data are for the most recent year available for 1987-2002.
ER.H2O.FWTL.K3-fj.name: Annual freshwater withdrawals
ER.H2O.FWTL.K3-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.

ER.H2O.FWTL.ZS-fj.def: Annual freshwater withdrawals refer to total water withdrawals, not counting evaporation losses from storage basins. Withdrawals also include water from desalination plants in countries where they are a significant source. Withdrawals can exceed 100 percent of total renewable resources where extraction from nonrenewable aquifers or desalination plants is considerable or where there is significant water reuse. Withdrawals for agriculture and industry are total withdrawals for irrigation and livestock production and for direct industrial use (including withdrawals for cooling thermoelectric plants). Withdrawals for domestic uses include drinking water, municipal use or supply, and use for public services, commercial establishments, and homes. Data are for the most recent year available for 1987-2002.
ER.H2O.FWTL.ZS-fj.name: Annual freshwater withdrawals
ER.H2O.FWTL.ZS-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.

ER.H2O.INTR.K3-fj.def: Renewable internal freshwater resources flows refer to internal renewable resources (internal river flows and groundwater from rainfall) in the country.
ER.H2O.INTR.K3-fj.name: Renewable internal freshwater resources, total
ER.H2O.INTR.K3-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.

ER.H2O.INTR.PC-fj.def: Renewable internal freshwater resources flows refer to internal renewable resources (internal river flows and groundwater from rainfall) in the country. Renewable internal freshwater resources per capita are calculated using the World Bank's population estimates.
ER.H2O.INTR.PC-fj.name: Renewable internal freshwater resources per capita
ER.H2O.INTR.PC-fj.source: Food and Agriculture Organization, AQUASTAT data.
